NOTES_JONAH = {
    1: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The phrase "the word of YHWH came" (wayehi devar-YHWH) is a standard prophetic formula appearing throughout the Twelve Prophets and the Former Prophets, marking divine commissioning. The name "Jonah" (yonah) means "dove," a detail with possible symbolic resonance given his role as a reluctant messenger. "Amittai" (amittay) means "my truth" or "my faithfulness," a name of ironic weight given Jonah\'s flight from YHWH\'s commission. (2 Kgs 14:25)',
        2: 'HISTORICAL: Nineveh was the capital of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, one of the most formidable and feared powers of the ancient Near East, located on the eastern bank of the Tigris River in modern-day northern Iraq. The phrase "their evil has come up before my face" echoes the language of Gen 18:20-21, where the outcry of Sodom rises to YHWH — positioning Nineveh typologically alongside the archetypal wicked city. THEOLOGICAL: The universality of YHWH\'s moral governance is asserted here: the God of Israel holds pagan nations accountable for their wickedness, a theme that runs through the prophets (Amos 1-2, Nahum).',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The repetition of "from the face of YHWH" (mippene YHWH) twice in this verse is theologically pointed — Jonah\'s flight is not merely geographic but is a rejection of covenantal presence and prophetic calling. The verb "went down" (yarad) is used three times in vv. 3-5, creating a descent motif that culminates in the depths of the sea — a literary and theological unraveling. TYPOLOGY: As Christ descended into death and the heart of the earth, Jonah\'s descent prefigures that pattern in reverse — Jonah flees into the deep, while Christ willingly enters it.',
        5: 'HEBREW: The word "tardemah" (Strong\'s H8639) denotes a supernaturally deep sleep, the same word used in Gen 2:21 when YHWH causes Adam to sleep before drawing out Eve, and in Gen 15:12 during the covenant with Abraham. Its use here may suggest Jonah\'s detachment from reality and covenant responsibility. TYPOLOGY: Jonah asleep in the storm-tossed vessel directly parallels Jesus asleep in the boat during the storm on the Sea of Galilee (Mark 4:38), a connection the gospel writers likely intended as deliberate typological echo.',
        7: 'HISTORICAL: The casting of lots (goralot) was a widely practiced method of divination throughout the ancient Near East to determine divine will or assign blame. Within Israelite theology, lots were understood to be under YHWH\'s sovereign direction (Prov 16:33), so the outcome is not mere chance but providential disclosure. The lot\'s fall upon Jonah functions as a divine verdict rendered through pagan means — YHWH\'s sovereignty extending even over the sailors\' casting.',
        9: 'HEBREW: "Ivri" (Hebrew, Strong\'s H5680) is the ethnic self-designation Jonah uses, rooted possibly in the name "Eber" (Gen 10:24) or in the term for one who "crosses over." This is a rare instance of an Israelite identifying himself by this term to foreigners. His confession — "YHWH, the God of the heavens, I fear, who made the sea and the dry land" — is richly ironic: Jonah confesses YHWH\'s sovereignty over the very sea he is fleeing across. THEOLOGICAL: The confession signals that Jonah\'s flight is not one of ignorance but willful rebellion against a God he knows to be omnipotent.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The sailors\' prayer to YHWH by name marks a remarkable theological moment — pagan mariners, who had each cried to their own god in v. 5, now address Israel\'s God directly by his covenant name. Their concern for "innocent blood" reflects awareness of moral law even outside the covenant community. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The language of accountability before YHWH as cosmic sovereign echoes the framework of Deut 32:8-9, wherein the nations are under both divine and mediating governance — yet YHWH remains the ultimate judge before whom all blood-guilt is reckoned.',
        16: 'HEBREW: "Yir\'ah gedolah" — a great fear — is the same construction used in Exod 14:31 after Israel witnesses YHWH\'s power at the sea. The sailors\' response of sacrifice and vows constitutes genuine religious conversion in the narrative\'s presentation. THEOLOGICAL: These pagan sailors come to fear and worship YHWH through the witness of a disobedient prophet — a profound irony that previews the book\'s theme that YHWH\'s mercy and revelation extend beyond Israel\'s borders (cf. Matt 8:11).',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: This verse is the foundation of Jesus\' "sign of Jonah" — cited explicitly in Matt 12:39-41, 16:4, and Luke 11:29-32 — where Jesus declares that as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of the great fish, so the Son of Man will be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth. The "great fish" (dag gadol) is not identified by species; the text\' emphasis falls on divine appointment ("wayeman YHWH" — "YHWH appointed"), stressing sovereign providence rather than natural explanation. HEBREW: The verb "mannah" (appointed, Strong\'s H4487) is used of YHWH\'s sovereign preparation throughout the book (also 4:6, 4:7, 4:8), forming a structural motif of divine orchestration over creation.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: "From the belly of Sheol I cried" — Jonah\'s prayer from the depths of the fish\'s belly is the primary typological anchor for Jesus\' declaration in Matt 12:40: "as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of the great fish, so will the Son of Man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth." The Hebrew she\'ol (H7585) refers to the realm of the dead, giving the descent a genuine mortuary weight beyond mere distress. THEOLOGICAL: Jonah\'s deliverance through death-and-return structures the entire theology of resurrection as YHWH\'s sovereign answer to the cry of the righteous from the lowest place.',
        3: 'HEBREW: The Hebrew nahar (H5104, "river" or "flood") here carries cosmic-ocean imagery drawn from ancient Near Eastern cosmology, where the chaotic deep-waters represent the realm opposing divine order. The phrase "all Your breakers and Your waves" (kol-mishbarekha we-gallekha) closely echoes Ps 42:7, suggesting a liturgical tradition of describing divine testing through overwhelming waters. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In the cosmological background of Ugaritic and Second Temple texts, the sea (yam) and its floods represent the chaotic anti-creation domain, here explicitly reframed as under YHWH\'s sovereign command — it is YHWH\'s breakers that overwhelm, not autonomous chaos.',
        5: 'HEBREW: Nephesh (H5315) here is translated "death" following the idiom le-nephesh — literally "to the soul/throat," an idiom for life-threatening extremity. Tehom (H8415, "the deep") is the same primordial deep of Gen 1:2, invoking the pre-creation abyss. THEOLOGICAL: Jonah\'s descent into the watery tehom recapitulates creation-in-reverse: the prophet sinks through the cosmic deep, mirroring the chaos from which YHWH ordered the world, making his retrieval a new-creation act.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: "You brought up my life from the pit (shachat)" — shachat (H7845) denotes the pit of destruction, synonymous with death and corruption. This language is directly echoed in Ps 16:10, "You will not abandon my soul to Sheol, nor let your Holy One see corruption," a verse Peter explicitly applies to the resurrection of Jesus in Acts 2:27. Jonah\'s ascent from the pit thus foreshadows the resurrection of the Messiah who descends fully into death and is raised incorruptible.',
        8: 'HEBREW: Hebel (H1892) means "vapor, breath, vanity" — the same term that frames Ecclesiastes ("vanity of vanities"). The phrase "vanities of emptiness" (shawe\' hebel) is a double intensification meaning utterly empty falsehoods, here referring to idols. Hesed (H2617) — steadfast covenant-love, loyalty, lovingkindness — is the great relational term of the covenant. THEOLOGICAL: The verse declares that idolatry is not merely moral failure but covenantal self-abandonment: to cling to empty things is to forfeit one\'s own hesed — the very relational identity one holds within YHWH\'s covenant community.',
        9: 'HEBREW: Yeshu\'ah (H3444, "salvation, deliverance") shares its root with the name Yeshua (Jesus), making this closing doxology linguistically resonant with the NT proclamation. The declaration "salvation belongs to YHWH" (le-YHWH ha-yeshu\'ah) is a covenantal affirmation that deliverance is not earned or seized but received as YHWH\'s sovereign gift. TYPOLOGY: Jonah\'s vow to sacrifice with thanksgiving from inside the fish — before his physical deliverance — models faith that anticipates resurrection, paralleling Christ\'s own trust in the Father through death (Ps 22:24; Heb 5:7).',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s direct speech to the fish (va-yomer YHWH la-dag) underscores the absolute sovereignty of YHWH over creation — the great sea creature, instrument of judgment, becomes instrument of restoration at a word. HISTORICAL: Ancient Near Eastern texts (Ugaritic, Mesopotamian) portray the sea and its creatures as autonomous or semi-divine powers; the text deliberately presents the fish as wholly obedient to YHWH\'s command, demythologizing the chaos-sea motif. STRUCTURE: The vomiting of Jonah onto dry land (yabbashah) inverts the narrative of chapter 1 — the descent into the sea is reversed into emergence onto land, structurally enacting death-and-resurrection before Jonah arrives at Nineveh.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "a second time" (Heb. שֵׁנִית, shenit) is theologically loaded — YHWH\'s recommission of Jonah demonstrates the irresistibility of divine calling and the grace of second chances. This parallels Peter\'s restoration (John 21:15-19) and underscores that YHWH\'s redemptive purposes cannot be thwarted by human flight or failure.',
        3: 'HISTORICAL: "A great city to elohim" (עִיר־גְּדוֹלָה לֵאלֹהִים) likely employs a Semitic superlative idiom, meaning "an exceedingly great city," though some scholars read it as indicating divine ownership or cosmic significance. Archaeological evidence from ancient Nineveh (modern Kuyunjik, near Mosul) confirms a massive metropolis; the "three days\' journey" likely refers to its administrative district, not the city proper. Nineveh served as the Assyrian capital under Sennacherib (ca. 700 BC).',
        4: 'HEBREW: The verb הָפַךְ (hafak, Strong\'s H2015), translated "overthrown," is the same verb used for the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah (Gen 19:25). Forty (אַרְבָּעִים, arba\'im) is a number of trial and probation throughout Scripture — forty years in the wilderness, forty days of Moses on Sinai, forty days of Elijah\'s journey. The brevity and bluntness of Jonah\'s proclamation is striking: only five Hebrew words in the original.',
        5: 'TYPOLOGY: The repentance of Nineveh at the preaching of Jonah stands as a type prefiguring the Gentile reception of the gospel. Jesus explicitly invokes this event: "The men of Nineveh will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and behold, something greater than Jonah is here" (Matt 12:41). The faith of pagan Nineveh condemns Israel\'s hardness of heart before the greater Prophet.',
        8: 'HEBREW: הָמָס (hamas, Strong\'s H2555) denotes violent wrongdoing, injustice, and lawless oppression — a morally loaded term also used of the pre-flood generation\'s corruption (Gen 6:11). The call to turn (שׁוּב, shuv, Strong\'s H7725) from hamas represents genuine covenantal repentance language, though addressed to a Gentile nation, underscoring YHWH\'s universal moral governance over all peoples.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Who knows?" (מִי־יוֹדֵעַ, mi-yodea) reflects genuine theological humility — the king does not presume upon divine mercy but appeals to it. This mirrors Joel 2:14, using nearly identical language in a Jewish context. The relenting of God (נָחַם, nacham, Strong\'s H5162) is not a change in his eternal nature but a covenantal responsiveness: when the conditions that warranted judgment change, so does the outworking of his purposes in history.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The verb וַיִּנָּחֶם (vayyinachem), from נָחַם (nacham), is anthropopathic language — God responding in a manner analogous to human relenting. This is theologically consistent with the Mosaic revelation of YHWH\'s character in Exodus 34:6-7 as compassionate and slow to anger. Jonah\'s anger at this mercy in chapter 4 reveals that he understood perfectly what YHWH was doing — and resented it, exposing the ethnocentric failure of his own heart.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "It was evil to Jonah" uses the root ra\'ah (H7489/H7451), creating a deliberate wordplay: YHWH "relents of the evil (ra\'ah)" he threatened (3:10), yet Jonah finds this very mercy to be "evil" to himself. The narrator exposes the grotesque irony of the prophet\'s heart through shared vocabulary.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jonah\'s prayer quotes the foundational divine self-disclosure of Exodus 34:6-7 — the "thirteen attributes of mercy" in Jewish tradition. Jonah knew YHWH\'s character perfectly; his flight was not ignorance but active resistance to God\'s grace extending beyond Israel. The hesed (H2617) of YHWH is the theological center of the entire book.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Is it good that it burns hot to you?" — the verb charah (H2734) means to burn with anger or heat. YHWH\'s question is left unanswered here, a rhetorical suspension that frames the enacted parable of vv. 5-11. The same question recurs in v. 9, forming a literary bracket.',
        6: 'HEBREW: The qiqayon (H7021) is a plant of uncertain identification — possibly the castor oil plant (Ricinus communis), a fast-growing leafy shrub native to the ANE. The root "appointed" (manah, H4487) is the same verb used for the great fish (1:17), the worm (4:7), and the east wind (4:8), emphasizing YHWH\'s sovereign orchestration of all created agents. TYPOLOGY: The plant\'s sudden appearance and disappearance mirrors the transience of earthly comfort, pointing to the only lasting shelter found in YHWH himself.',
        7: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The fourfold use of "appointed" (manah) across chapters 1-4 — fish, plant, worm, wind — frames YHWH as the sovereign Lord of the divine council who deploys all natural and spiritual agents as his servants, subordinate to his redemptive purposes.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jonah\'s blunt reply — "It is good that it burns hot to me unto death" — is a confession of idolatrous self-pity. He would rather die than witness Gentile salvation. Jesus uses this same Ninevite repentance as a judgment against unbelieving Israel (Matt 12:41; Luke 11:32), inverting Jonah\'s contempt into a standard of faith.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The closing rhetorical question is unanswered, left open to implicate every reader. The "one hundred and twenty thousand who do not know their right hand from their left" likely refers to children too young for moral discernment, signaling the massive scale of Nineveh\'s population. YHWH\'s concern for "much cattle" further grounds divine compassion in creational care, not merely covenantal categories. TYPOLOGY: Christ, the greater Jonah, does not flee from Gentile sinners but pursues them — fulfilling what Jonah only foreshadowed in his reluctant, resentful mission (Matt 12:41; John 3:16; Rom 15:9-12).',
    },
}